Observations:¶

There are many features, some might be useful and other not: we need to select only relevant ones. To do that, we can use the chi2 test of independance.

Other observations:

  • Sparse City_Code_Patient: Could potentially identify patients & induce overfitting => Remove infrequent data
  • Visitors with Patient is very skewed => Group in 5 groups: 0, 1, 2, 3, 4+
  • Available Extra Rooms in Hospital is also skewed => Group in 4 groups with qcut

Multivariate analysis¶

Here, we plot the conditional distribution of the target variable w.r.t. supposedly dependent variables ($P(Y|X)$), and we compute the *Chi2 statistic to test if two variables are independent, and the **Spearman rank to test correlation.

*Pearson’s chi-squared test is a goodness-of-fit test for a multinomial distribution with given probabilities; that is, it assesses the null hypothesis that the observed frequencies (counts) are obtained by independent sampling of N observations from a categorical distribution with given expected frequencies.

**The Spearman rank-order correlation coefficient is a nonparametric measure of the monotonicity of the relationship between two datasets. Like other correlation coefficients, this one varies between -1 and +1 with 0 implying no correlation. The p-value roughly indicates the probability of an uncorrelated system producing datasets that have a Spearman correlation at least as extreme as the one computed from these datasets.

In [11]:
def plot_conditional_distributions(y, x, data, layout=None, figsize=None, stat="probability"):
    # Plot the conditional probability of y given x (P(y|x)) for all values of x
    probability_table = (
        data[[x, y]]
        .assign(dummy=1)
        .pivot_table(index=y, columns=x, aggfunc="sum")
        .droplevel(0, 1)
        .apply(lambda x: x/x.sum())
    )
    
    plot = probability_table.plot.bar(
        subplots=True, sharey=True, 
        layout=layout, figsize=figsize, 
        width=1, edgecolor='k', 
        ylabel=y, xlabel="", 
        title=[""] * probability_table.shape[1]
    )
    [ax.tick_params(length=0) for ax in plot.flatten()]
    plt.tight_layout()
    return plot
In [12]:
from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency
from itertools import combinations

def test_independence(y, x, data):
    observed = (
        data[[x, y]]
        .assign(dummy=1)
        .pivot_table(index=y, columns=x, aggfunc="sum")
        .droplevel(0, 1)
    )
#     return observed
    chi2, p, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(observed)

    expected = pd.DataFrame(expected, index=observed.index, columns=observed.columns)
    
    print(f"Chi-square Statistic: {chi2}")
    print(f"P-value: {p}")
    print(f"Degrees of Freedom: {dof}")
    print("Observed - Expected:")
    plt.figure()
    ax = sns.heatmap((1 - expected / observed).T, cbar=False, annot=True, square=True, cmap="vlag", vmin=-1, vmax=1)
    ax.tick_params(length=0)
    ax.set_title(rf"$\chi^2={chi2:,.2f} p={p:.0e}$")
    if p < .05:
        print(f'Reject H0: "{x}" and "{y}" are not independent')
    return chi2, p

Comparing Age and Stay, we observed that most patient where aged 31-50 and stayed for 21-30 days. Should the two variables be independent, the 1 - Expected/Observed table (2nd graph below) should be zeros everywhere. As we can see, this is not the case and we observe more elderly patients remaining longer than what would be expected from independent distributions. We also see that younger patients tend to stay shorter than expected.

The $\chi^2$ test tells us whether two variables are independent, but more interestingly, it gives us a table of expected probabilities. We can use it to understand how one variable might be influenced by the other.

In the graphs below we see that we observed more people in surgery staying longer that would be expected from independent variables, and patients in the anesthesia department seem to have shorter stays than expected.

We can also compute the Spearman Rank for all variables to test the correlation of the variables. Below, we see that we can eliminate Bed Grade and City_Code_Patient.

In [21]:
from scipy.stats import spearmanr

def test_correlation(data, target_name, threshold=.05):
    columns = data.columns
    
    feats = [x for x in data.columns if x != target_name]
    
    R, p = (
        pd.DataFrame(x, index=columns, columns=columns)
        for x in spearmanr(data.dropna(how="any", axis=0))
    )

    df = pd.concat([df.loc[df.index != target_name, target_name] for df in (R, p)], axis=1)
    df.columns = ["R", "p"]
    df = df.sort_values("R")
    df["accept_H0"] = df["p"] < threshold
    plt.figure(figsize=(18, 10))
    ax = sns.barplot(df["R"], orient="h") #, annot=True, fmt=".3f", cbar=False, cmap="viridis")
    labels = list(map("{0[0]:.2%} (p={0[1]:.2%})".format, df.values))
    labels = ax.bar_label(ax.containers[0], labels, label_type="center", fontsize=10)
    for bar, label, accept in zip(ax.containers[0], labels, df["accept_H0"]):
        if not(accept):
            bar.set(facecolor=palette[1])
            label.set(color="red")
    return df

test_correlation(train.dropna(how="any", axis=0), target_name);

Machine Learning¶

Now I got a better understanding of the data and what transformation need to be done. First, we encode the data: one-hot encoding for categorical data, ordinal encoding for ordinal data and scale numerical data. The class below implement that. Then we encode the training and evaluation sets.

In [23]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import OrdinalEncoder, OneHotEncoder, StandardScaler
from sklearn.exceptions import NotFittedError


class XYEncoder:
    """
    Helper class to encode a bunch of categorical and ordinal variables compatible with Scikit Learn
    categorical variables --> OneHot encoded
    ordinal variables --> Int encoded
    numerical variables --> Standard scaled
    """
    
    def __init__(self, categorical_variables:List[str], ordinal_variables:List[str], numerical_variables:List[str]):
        
        self.categorical_variables = categorical_variables
        self.ordinal_variables = ordinal_variables
        self.numerical_variables = numerical_variables
        
    def get_variable_groups(self):
        return self.categorical_variables, self.ordinal_variables, self.numerical_variables

    def get_encoders(self):
        self.assert_fitted()
        return self._categorical_encoder, self._ordinal_encoder, self._numerical_encoder
        
    def assert_fitted(self):
        if not hasattr(self, "encoders_"):
            raise NotFittedError()
    
    def fit(self, data:pd.DataFrame) -> pd.DataFrame:

        # Initialize the encoders
        # Ignoring the unknowns makes sure that all values are zeros for missing values
        self._categorical_encoder = OneHotEncoder(sparse_output=False, handle_unknown="ignore")
        self._ordinal_encoder = OrdinalEncoder()
        self._numerical_encoder = StandardScaler()
        self.encoders_ = [self._categorical_encoder, self._ordinal_encoder, self._numerical_encoder]

        # Fit the encoders
        for names, encoder in zip(self.get_variable_groups(), self.get_encoders()):
            encoder.fit(data[names])

        return self
    
    def transform(self, data:pd.DataFrame) -> pd.DataFrame:
        # Safety check
        self.assert_fitted()

        # Encode and store in a new dataframe
        encoded_data = []
        for names, encoder in zip(self.get_variable_groups(), self.get_encoders()):
        
            encoded_data.append(pd.DataFrame(
                encoder.transform(data[names]),
                columns=encoder.get_feature_names_out()
            ))
        
        return pd.concat(encoded_data, axis=1)
    
    def fit_transform(self, data: pd.DataFrame) -> pd.DataFrame:
        self.fit(data)
        return self.transform(data)

Feature selection¶

During the exploration, we have seen that potentially many features should not be included in the model, and only some might actually have some chance of explaining the target variable.

Below, we select the features in multiple steps:

  • We use what we learned from the exploration and from common sense to remove some columns
  • We train a machine learning model with the resulting features
  • We use the learned parameters to identify useless features and prune even more the feature set
In [24]:

Classification model with a decision tree¶

In the next cell, we use GridSearchCV to search the parameter space and find the best parameters for our predictive model.

  • We use SelectPercentile because it is simple and fast
  • We use DecisionTreeClassifier because it is very fast and quite reliable
  • We select the model that maximizes the micro F1 score because it is a reliable metric for multiclass classification
In [26]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

search_space = {
    "tree__min_samples_split": [500, 1000, 2000, 3000],  # Min samples for splitting
    "tree__max_features": [10, 20, 25]  # Max features to consider for splitting
}

clf = Pipeline([
    ("tree", DecisionTreeClassifier())
])
# Select the optimal percentage of features with grid search
gs = GridSearchCV(clf, search_space, cv=3, scoring="f1_micro", n_jobs=-1)
gs.fit(X_train, y_train)  # set the best parameters
pd.DataFrame(gs.cv_results_)[
    [*map("param_{}".format, search_space), "mean_test_score", "std_test_score", "rank_test_score"]
].sort_values("rank_test_score").head(10)

Results¶

The decision tree only gives a performance of 39% accuracy on the evaluation set. Since the performance on the training set does not get higher except by making the model overfit, it is unlikely that we can get better results, although we can try with a random forest.

As we have observed during the exploration, the number of visitors is the feature with the most importance, followed by Ward_Type_Q and Admission_Deposit.
